        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Some MSS., the LXX., and the Vulg. read “and these (were) the sons of Etam;” other MSS., with the Syriac and Arabic versions, have “the sons of the father of Etam.” Both variants look like evasions of a difficulty. The unusual expression “and these—Abi-Etam” may be a brief way of stating that the clans whose names are given were the dominant houses of Etam (or Abi-etam; compare Abiezer, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 7:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 8:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Etam is known from the history of Samson (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 15:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Chronicles 11:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); Jezreel—not Ahab’s capital—from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 15:56",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and as the city of Ahinoam, wife of David, from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Chronicles 3:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Both places were in the hill-country of Judah. The other three names are unknown.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Their sister.—Their sister-town (see 1Chronicles 1:39; 1Chronicles 1:52, and Notes).",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Their sister.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
